              </svg>
              <span>{post.date}</span>
            </div>
            
            <div class="flex items-center">
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-4 w-4 mr-1" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 8v4l3 3m6-3a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" />
              </svg>
              <span>{post.readingTime}</span>
            </div>
            
            <div class="flex items-center">
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-4 w-4 mr-1" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M16 7a4 4 0 11-8 0 4 4 0 018 0zM12 14a7 7 0 00-7 7h14a7 7 0 00-7-7z" />
              </svg>
              <span>{post.author}</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-6">
            {post.tags.map(tag => (
              <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-black/5 dark:bg-[#3be9d1]/10 rounded-full text-xs text-black/70 dark:text-[#3be9d1]/90">
                {tag}
              </span>
            ))}
          </div>
          
          <div class="w-full aspect-video bg-black/5 dark:bg-white/5 rounded-lg overflow-hidden mb-6">
            <img src="/placeholder-image.svg" alt={post.title} class="w-full h-full object-cover" />
          </div>
        </header>
        
        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-black/80 dark:text-white/80">
          <p>
            The legal industry is at a crossroads. With the rapid advancement of artificial intelligence, machine learning, and other emerging technologies, the practice of law is undergoing a transformation unlike any seen before. This evolution presents both challenges and opportunities for legal professionals, technologists, and the clients they serve.
          </p>
          
          <h2>The Current State of Legal Technology</h2>
          <p>
            Today's legal technology landscape is characterized by a growing ecosystem of tools designed to enhance efficiency, accuracy, and accessibility. From contract analysis software to AI-powered legal research platforms, these technologies are already beginning to reshape how legal work is performed.
          </p>
          <p>
            Document automation has become increasingly sophisticated, allowing for the generation of complex legal documents with minimal human intervention. E-discovery tools leverage natural language processing to sift through millions of documents, identifying relevant information with a precision that would be impossible for human reviewers working alone.
          </p>
          
          <h2>Artificial Intelligence and the Practice of Law</h2>
          <p>
            AI's impact on the legal profession is multifaceted. While some fear that automation will replace traditional legal roles, the more likely outcome is a redistribution of tasks and a redefinition of how legal services are delivered.
          </p>
          <p>
            Machine learning algorithms are now capable of predicting litigation outcomes with impressive accuracy, analyzing patterns across thousands of past cases to identify factors that influence judicial decisions. This predictive capability enables lawyers to make more informed strategic recommendations to their clients.
          </p>
          <p>
            Natural language processing is advancing rapidly, with systems now able to understand and interpret legal texts with nuance. These capabilities are being integrated into research tools that can answer complex legal questions and identify relevant precedents far more quickly than traditional methods.
          </p>
          
          <h2>Blockchain and Smart Contracts</h2>
          <p>
            Blockchain technology offers the potential for self-executing "smart contracts" that automatically enforce their terms when predefined conditions are met. This could dramatically reduce disputes and the need for traditional contract enforcement mechanisms.
          </p>
          <p>
            The immutability of blockchain records also presents interesting possibilities for evidence verification and chain of custody documentation in litigation contexts.
          </p>
          
          <h2>Access to Justice</h2>
          <p>
            Perhaps the most promising aspect of legal technology is its potential to address the persistent access to justice gap. Automated tools can make basic legal services more affordable and accessible to underserved populations.
          </p>
          <p>
            Expert systems are being developed that can guide non-lawyers through common legal processes, from filing for divorce to creating a simple will, democratizing access to fundamental legal protections.
          </p>
          
          <h2>Ethical and Regulatory Challenges</h2>
          <p>
            The integration of advanced technology into legal practice brings significant ethical and regulatory challenges. Issues of algorithmic bias, data privacy, unauthorized practice of law, and the appropriate boundaries of automation all need thoughtful resolution.
          </p>
          <p>
            Bar associations and legal regulators are only beginning to grapple with these questions, and the legal profession will need to develop new ethical frameworks suited to a technologically augmented practice environment.
          </p>
          
          <h2>The Path Forward</h2>
          <p>
            The future of legal technology will likely be characterized by a symbiotic relationship between human lawyers and technological tools. The most successful legal professionals will be those who embrace technology as a means to enhance their services rather than viewing it as a threat.
          </p>
          <p>
            Law schools are increasingly incorporating technology education into their curricula, recognizing that tomorrow's lawyers will need to be technologically literate and adaptable. Interdisciplinary collaboration between legal professionals, technologists, and ethicists will be crucial in shaping how these tools develop.
          </p>
          
          <h2>Conclusion</h2>
          <p>
            The transformation of the legal industry through technology is inevitable, but its exact form remains to be determined. By actively engaging with these developments and maintaining a focus on core legal values like justice, fairness, and client service, the legal profession can harness technological change to create a more efficient, accessible, and just legal system.
          </p>
          <p>
            The future of legal technology is not just about automation or efficiencyâ€”it's about reimagining how legal services can be delivered in ways that better serve both practitioners and the public.
          </p>
        </div>
        
